Statistical analysis of water discharge of surface streams

Task:

  • find a dataset about a river's water level
  • analyse the various timeseries data by fitting the right/suitable distribution onto it.
  • draw some conclusions about the weather near the river/measurement station

A list of statistical distributions

  • Each hyperlink directs to the corresponding Wikipedia page of the provided distribution.
  • PMF: probabitity mass function (for discreted distribution)
  • PDF: probabitity density function (for countinuous distribution)

Fermi-Dirac statistics $$ \bar{n}_i = \frac{1}{e^{(\varepsilon_i - \mu) / k_\text{B} T} + 1} $$

Bose-Einstein statistics $$ \bar{n}_i = \frac{g_i}{e^{(\varepsilon_i-\mu) / k_\text{B} T} - 1} $$

Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution $$ \text{PDF} = \sqrt{\frac{2}{\pi}} \, \frac{x^2}{a^3} \, \exp\left(\frac{-x^2}{2a^2} \right) $$

Plancks law $$ u_\nu(\nu, T) = \frac{ 8 \pi h \nu^3}{c^3} \frac 1{\exp\left(\frac{h\nu}{k_\mathrm B T}\right) - 1} $$

Binomial distribution

  • discrete variables
  • number of successes of n independent experiments $$ \text{PMF} = \binom{n}{k} p^k q^{n-k} $$

Cauchy distribution

  • ration of normally distributed variables
  • shape of spectral lines $$ \text{PDF} = \frac{1}{\pi\gamma\,\left[1 + \left(\frac{x-x_0}{\gamma}\right)^2\right]}\! $$

Gamma distribution $$ \text{PDF} = \frac{1}{\Gamma(k) \theta^k} x^{k - 1} e^{-x/\theta}$$

Geometric distribution

  • number of trials before the first success in Bernoulli trials $$ \text{PDF} = (1 - p)^{k-1}p $$

Chi-squared distribution

  • sum of squares of independent standard normal variables
  • how to construct confidence intervals $$ \text{PDF} = \frac{1}{2^{k/2}\Gamma(k/2)}\; x^{k/2-1} e^{-x/2}\; $$

Exponential distribution $$ \text{PDF} = \lambda e^{-\lambda x} $$

Gumbel distribution

  • expectation value of the maximum/minimum of samples drawn from a parent distribution with exp tail $$ \text{PDF} = \frac{1}{\beta}e^{-(z+e^{-z})} $$ where $z=\frac{x-\mu}{\beta}$

Lvy distribution

  • heavy-tailed distribution $$ \text{PDF} = \sqrt{\frac{c}{2\pi}}~~\frac{e^{-\frac{c}{2(x-\mu)}}}{(x-\mu)^{3/2}} $$

Logistic distribution

  • categorical dependent variables
  • logistic regression $$ \text{PDF} = \frac{e^{-(x-\mu)/s}} {s\left(1+e^{-(x-\mu)/s}\right)^2} $$

Log normal distribution

  • product of many independent variables
  • size distribution of particles $$ \frac{ 1 }{\ x\sigma\sqrt{2\pi\ }\ }\ \exp\left( - \frac{ \left( \ln x - \mu\ \right)^2}{ 2 \sigma^2 } \right) $$

Normal distribution $$ \text{PDF} = \frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}} e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{x - \mu}{\sigma}\right)^2}$$

Pareto distribution

  • heavy-tailed, decreasing power-law
  • degree distribution of social networks $$ \text{PDF} = \frac{\alpha x_\mathrm{m}^\alpha}{x^{\alpha+1}} $$

Poisson distribution $$ \text{PMF} = \frac{\lambda^{k}e^{-\lambda}}{k!} $$

Student t-distribution

  • average of a normally distributed population
  • n is small $$ \text{PDF} = \frac{\Gamma \left(\frac{\ \nu+1\ }{ 2 } \right)} {\sqrt{\pi\ \nu\ }\ \Gamma \left(\frac{ \nu }{\ 2\ } \right)}\ \left(\ 1 + \frac{~ x^2\ }{ \nu }\ \right)^{-\frac{\ \nu+1\ }{ 2 }}$$

Continuous Uniform distribution $$ \text{PDF} = \begin{cases} \frac{1}{b-a} & \text{for } x \in [a,b] \\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{cases}$$

Weibull distribution

  • any of n iid variables being above a certain limit
  • first failure of a system of n identical components $$ \text{PDF} = \begin{cases} \frac{k}{\lambda}\left(\frac{x}{\lambda}\right)^{k-1}e^{-(x/\lambda)^k}, & x\geq0,\\ 0, & x<0.\end{cases} $$

# packages
import os
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

from scipy.optimize import curve_fit 
from scipy.signal import find_peaks

from scipy.stats import cauchy, gamma, chi2, expon, gumbel_l, levy, logistic, lognorm, norm, pareto, t, weibull_min
distribution = [cauchy, gamma, chi2, expon, gumbel_l, levy, logistic, lognorm, norm,  pareto, t, weibull_min]
distribution_names = ['Cauchy', 'Gamma', '$\chi^2$', 'Exponential', 'Gumbel', 'Lvy', 'Logistic', 'Log normal', 'Normal', 'Pareto', 'Student-t', 'Weibull']

FS = 15 # fontsize for plot


# Fitting functions
def exponential(x, l1, l2, c):
    return l1 * np.exp(-l2*x) + c

def lin(x, a, b):
    return a*x + b

Excercise 1

For the purposes of the current excercises, select a stream from a rainy area with relatively small discharge so that the effect of short but strong storms is visible. Good choices are small rivers from the north-eastern US, e.g. site 01589440. Retrieve at least 10 years of data.

Large amounts of historical surface water data are available from the United States Geological Survey (USGS) at https://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis The goal of the project is to retrieve samples from the web interface manually, and then later automate the process by calling the web service as described at https://help.waterdata.usgs.gov/faq/automated-retrievals.

The service is explained in more detail here: https://waterservices.usgs.gov/rest/Site-Service.html

The location: Jones Falls at Sorrento

In[3]:
# Download data with a given time period
start_date = ['2010', '01', '01']
end_date   = ['2019', '12', '31']

filename = f"./data/jones_falls_{''.join(start_date)}-{''.join(end_date)}.txt"

if not os.path.exists(filename):
    import requests
    url = "https://nwis.waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/uv/"
    params = {
        "format": 'rdb',
        "site_no": '01589440',
        "parameterCd": '00065',
        "begin_date": ''.join(start_date),
        "end_date": ''.join(end_date),
        "siteStatus": 'all'
    }
    response = requests.get(url, params=params)

    with open(filename, "w") as file:
        file.write(response.text)
    df = pd.read_csv(filename, sep='\t', skiprows=[30], comment='#', parse_dates=['datetime'])
    
else:
    df = pd.read_csv(filename, sep='\t', skiprows=[30], comment='#', parse_dates=['datetime'])

# Fitting functions
y_max_boundary = 2600
idx = np.where(bins <= y_max_boundary)[0][-1]
x_axis = np.linspace(0, bins[idx], y_max_boundary)

fit_params = []
fitted_data = []

fig, ax = plt.subplots(3, 4, figsize=(18, 12))
for i, dist in enumerate(distribution):
    params = dist.fit(hist_log[:idx])
    fit_params.append(params)
    fitted_data.append(dist.pdf(x_axis, *params))
    row = i // 4
    col = i % 4
    ax[row, col].plot(x_axis, fitted_data[i], c='r', label='fitted function')
    ax[row, col].plot(bins[:idx], hist_log[:idx], 'o--', c='b', label='data')
    ax[row, col].set_title(distribution_names[i]+' distribution')
    ax[row, col].set_xlabel('water discharge [ft$^3$/s]')
    ax[row, col].set_ylabel('# of events [$10^x$]')
    ax[row, col].legend()
    ax[row, col].grid()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

In[11]:
popt_exp, pcov_exp = curve_fit(exponential,  bins[:idx], hist_log[:idx], p0=(5, 0.01, 0.3))
perr_exp = np.sqrt(np.diag(pcov_exp))
print('Fit params:')
for i, (opt, err) in enumerate(zip(popt_exp, perr_exp)):
    print(f"Param_{i+1} = {round(opt, 5)} \pm {round(err, 5)}")
    
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
plt.plot(x_axis, exponential(x_axis, *popt_exp), c='r', label='fitted exponential\n $\lambda_1 e^{-\lambda_2 x} + c$')
plt.plot(bins[:idx], hist_log[:idx], 'o--', c='b', label='data')
plt.title('Histogram of water discharge values\nModified exponential distribution\nlog-lin scale', fontsize=FS+3)
plt.xlabel('Water discharge [ft$^3/$s]', fontsize=FS)
plt.ylabel('Frequency [$10^x$]', fontsize=FS)
plt.legend(fontsize=FS)
plt.grid()
plt.show()

Excercise 4

In case of small streams, storms and passing weather fronts with rain can significantly increase water discharge on a short time scale. Develop a simple algorithm to detect rainy events in the data. Plot the original time series and mark rainy events!

In[13]:
t_diff_in_hours = 3 # hour

water_discharge_diff = np.round(abs(np.diff(df.water_discharge[::(t_diff_in_hours*4)])), 1)
dates_wd_diff = df.date[::(t_diff_in_hours*4)][:-1].values

dates_wd_diff_wo0 = dates_wd_diff[water_discharge_diff != 0]
# water_discharge_diff without zeros
water_discharge_diff_wo0 = water_discharge_diff[water_discharge_diff != 0]

                                                        # ~~ only one peak per day
peaks = find_peaks(water_discharge_diff_wo0, height=2, distance=(24/t_diff_in_hours))

# Rainy days 
rainy_days_pct = len(dates_wd_diff_wo0[peaks[0]])/(len(df.date)/(4*24))*100

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
plt.plot(dates_wd_diff_wo0, water_discharge_diff_wo0, 'x--', c='b', label='data')
plt.scatter(dates_wd_diff_wo0[peaks[0]], peaks[1]['peak_heights'], marker='o', color='r', label=f'rainy events\nN={len(dates_wd_diff_wo0[peaks[0]])} days')

passed_hours_between_rainy_events = []
rainy_date = []
for i in range(len(rainy_events_1)):
    for j in range(i-30, i+30):
        if (rainy_events_1[i] - rainy_events_2[j%len_re_2]) < np.timedelta64(1, 'D'):
            hours = rainy_events_2[j].astype('datetime64[h]').astype(int) % 24
            minutes = rainy_events_2[j].astype('datetime64[m]').astype(int) % 60
            passed_hours_between_rainy_events.append(hours+minutes/60)
